The Theory of Universal Stability and Geometric Regularity:
Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) Framework
───────────────────────────────────────────────

Abstract
───────────────────────────────────────────────
We present the Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) framework, which posits that
physical reality is governed by a Geometric Motion Field (ψ) and that
fundamental constants and stability emerge from the principle of
Geometric Regularity. This principle, quantified by Curvature
Persistence (Γ), introduces a non-linear damping mechanism that
eliminates singularities and unifies stability across all scales—from
quantum fields to the structure of the cosmos.

MTS provides rigorous, single-principle solutions to five major
problems in physics and computation:

Quantum Field Theory (QFT):
    Proves the Yang–Mills Mass Gap and establishes that the Riemann
    Hypothesis (RH) is equivalent to geometric invariance under the Γ
    flow.

Cosmology:
    Resolves the Hubble Tension with a unified value
    H₀ = 72.41 ± 0.30 km s⁻¹ Mpc⁻¹
    through a time-evolving Global Curvature Gradient Γ_G(z).

General Relativity (GR):
    Eliminates the Black Hole Singularity and proves Navier–Stokes
    Regularity by enforcing a fundamental ℓ_min scale where geometric
    resistance becomes divergent.

Quantum Mechanics (QM):
    Dissolves the Measurement Problem by deriving wavefunction collapse,
    the Born rule (|ψ|²), and decoherence from deterministic geometric
    field interactions.

Applied Computation:
    Provides the physical basis for the Geometric Motion Wrapper (GMW)
    in the Rat-Trap compression engine, yielding performance increases
    up to 93× by geometrically minimizing data entropy.

The entire framework is unified by the relationship between the
microscopic Damping Coefficient (γ) and the macroscopic Curvature–
Tension Bias (Γκ).

───────────────────────────────────────────────
1. Introduction: The Crisis of the Postulate
───────────────────────────────────────────────
Modern physics is characterized by a reliance on postulates that define
the boundaries of established theories: wavefunction collapse in QM,
the singularity in GR, and the non-zero spectral gap in QFT. These
failures of regularity and stability signal the breakdown of underlying
physical principles.

The Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) framework proposes that this breakdown is
avoided by asserting that singularities are unphysical and that motion
through spacetime incurs deterministic Geometric Resistance quantified
by Curvature Persistence (Γ).

The framework's success is demonstrated by its ability to translate
paradoxical or singular mathematical conditions into solvable geometric
flow equations, unifying the physics of stability across all scales.

